<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Purpose: 		Inquiry - Select Committee - Local Government Procurement</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written submission from Halton Borough Council (LPG 26)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Purpose of the Report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Halton Borough Council wishes to submit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> evidence to the Select Committee in relation to the inquiry into </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Local Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Procurement. This evidence outlines </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">our procurement journey, demonstrates our best practice and how we have secured </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">value for money through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">commercial procurement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> concept. We have developed this in-house and are now working with a number of public sector partners to align their processes, practices and rules to ours in order to share our concept and replicate our success delivering further efficiencies and savings in other organisations.</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Executive Summary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Opportunities for Consideration:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Local Government need to r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ecognis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> embrac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e the fact</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that procurement is a strategic function </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and will support the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> deliver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">y of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> service excellence and can be used as a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">vehicle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> for change and integration. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">They need to embrace clear g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">overnance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and accountability.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ‘campaign’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">should be established and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">led nationally but delivered by local government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">advocates and champions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to educate and up skill officers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in all local government organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">andate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> should be established</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that all public sector organisations should align/adopt procurement rules </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">that are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">simplified</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and consider our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">two tier</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">approach (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">above EU and below EU </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">– Risk Based Sourcing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Spend analysis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">is critical and should be used</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> drive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">procurement planning priorities across all organisations. This will deliver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> economies of scale both in-house and in collaboration with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">other public sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">partners.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Improved contract management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> is essential </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">to ensure we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">improve relationships with the supply market, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">maintain outputs, give challenge and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ensure a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">continuous review.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A commitment to resourcing this concept</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">is paramount in order to allow this whole organisational change approach to be embedded. C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ommercial procurement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">needs the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> capacity and capability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of key staff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> within each organisation or in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> partnership with other organisations to enable this to happen. Long term skills investment in procurement is key in order to build capacity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Supplier Relationship Management is essential with due consideration specifically for SMEs and the Community, Voluntary and Social Enterprise (VCSE) sectors. A commitment to transparency and proportionality i.e. simplification of process and rules is key.  </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Overview of Halton’s Commercial Procurement Concept</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">:</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Halton Borough Council has placed Commercial Procurement at the heart of its business since April 2010. It continues to be one of the Council’s key solutions to avoid reductions to frontline services and protecting the vulnerable. It will remain to be at the centre of our organisation as we look to balance budgets year on year.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Halton benefits from strong leadership and a clear direction of support from Executive Board and Chief Officers as well as a dynamic vision from their Head of Procurement who has orchestrated her ideas into reality leading whole organisational change through improved strategic procurement. This has delivered significant cashable and non-cashable savings leading to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">improved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">service excellence.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">   </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">From </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">April 2010 a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> commercial approach to procurement was diagnosed, designed and then implemented across the whole organisation. This commenced with a review of spend, structures, processes and resources as a ‘health check’ guiding us on ‘quick wins’ but leading to a whole organisational change management programme, from education, communication &amp; training, ‘rules’ review and challenge in order to deliver significant outcomes. The application of commercial procurement has allowed us to take a stepped approach to change and has delivered a best practice concept that could be modelled into any organisation. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">This concept has been underpinned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">by Six Key Building Blocks: </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Organisation</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Halton recognised that procurement is a strategic function and is committed to placing it at the centre of its activities. This work stream was successful from:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Clear and highly effective leadership from the Head of Procurement across the whole organisation with the support from Elected Members and Management Team.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The development of capacity and capability of the Procurement Division to ensure clear and expert guidance from the centre.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A desktop review of ‘rules’ spend analysis, processes and resources was undertaken in order to create a delivery plan.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A commercial concept embedded across the whole organisation for all spend through a centralised team via The Chest e-portal system establishing a ‘one way’ approach.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A focussed communication and education strategy rolled out ‘top-down’ including training for 300+ k</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ey buyers, Senior Officers and E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">lected Members.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Governance and Process</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Halton has</span><a href="http://www.businessdictionary.com/definition/framework.html"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> embraced the importance of robust governance and work practices to support a commercial approach to procurement making this a key strategic function. Procurement Standing Orders review was paramount to our success as this set down new work parameters in order to secure better ‘gate-keeping’ which include:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">obust but simplified ‘rules’ developed to remove unnecessary procurement practices for spend below EU </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">financial t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">hresholds i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.e. formal tenders only undertaken for spend above EU </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">financial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Thresholds. (£173,934 Goods and Services; £4,348,350 Works).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A risk based sourcing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(RBS) concept implemented for all spend from £1,000 to EU financial thresholds which removes the PQQ, makes the quotation/sourcing activity proportionate to risk, i.e. only evaluate what is essential criteria.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Embedding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the principles of EU Law; equality, transparency, proportionality; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">free movement and non-discrimination in all procurement activities in relationship to all of our </span><a href="http://www.businessdictionary.com/definition/stakeholder.html"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">stakeholders</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A commitment to push</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> all spending above £1,000 via T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he Chest to aid complete transparen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cy and opportunity to suppliers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to quote or tender.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Implementation of new</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> waiver (permission to not follow parts of Standing Orders)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> procedures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> which allow decision making at a more appropriate level.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Operatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">nal Directors for spend below £2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">0,000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> for emergencies/Divisional Managers for spend below £5,000 for non-emergencies)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">These can be made with retrospective waiver reporting.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A Best and Final Offer (BAFO) approach to procurement has been adopted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> via The Chest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, to ensure we take every opportunity to drive the price down whilst maintaining quality in a controlled and fully auditable environment, which was commended by the Audit Commission.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Business Efficiency Board (BEB) scrutiny role - Members have engaged and scrutinised a selection of recent EU tender procurement activities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and RBS activities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in order to challenge and support current procurement practices. This is gaining wider political understanding and support to the process, complexities and risk of challenge.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A Procurement Strategy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">has been approved for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> 201</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">3- 2016</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> take</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> account of new legislation such as Localism Act 2011 and Public Services (Social Value) Act 2012 as well as Central Government Procurement Strategies and the pending review of Public Contract Regulations 2006 and the bi-annual review of EU Thresholds from January 2014.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Demand Management</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Having full visibility of spend has influenced our approach to procurement leading to the delivery of savings and achieving cost avoidance.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We have converted thinking from ‘what we want’ to ‘what we actually need’; which directly influences demand and consumption to reduce costs significantly. </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">An education campaign was provided to support the whole workforce by delivering training and direct support to ensure all officers know what should be done and why in order to remove the ‘always do what we have always done’ attitude. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Spend data on Agresso has been cleansed to ensure accurate data is used for planning procurement. This has been done by removing obsolete suppliers; locking down suppliers where we have a contract in place as a ‘gate keeper’ function and managing the supplier set up in procurement. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ompliance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> campaign commenced in 2012 in order to identify non-compliance with Procurement Standing Orders in order to drive a targeted approach to educate and support officers in improved procurement.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Supplier Relationship Management (SRM)</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">This is a proven way of working with key suppliers and is used in other public sector organisations to review overall business relationships, contractual arrangements, specifications, rates and expected outputs in order to mutually agree benefits which will result in savings for the Council as the customer. It will deliver greater value, meet strategic objectives and add social value. This will have greater leverage if we work with partners. In support of SRM:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We have commenced a structured approach to reviewing all of our contracts taking a SRM approach, using extensions where contracts allow negotiating and securing further gains from voluntary arrangements and on-going monitoring of KPIs. This will be developed in terms of rationalisation; performance management; partnering to align processes and gain economies of scale and developing regional relationships with our supply chain.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We launched a campaign “New Ways of Trading” in November 2010, reaching over 400 local businesses at a series of events/workshops covering Chest registration and use as well as PQQ coaching. Chest regist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ration has increased by over 161</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to date</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> since this this local engagement campaign commenced. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Halton </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">was awarded ‘Best Council to do Business With’ in May 2013 by Department for Communities and Local Government. Our spend with SMEs in 2012/13 was 89% (as at July 2013).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We have signed up to a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Liverpool City Region (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">LCR</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Charter for Employment and Skills </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">through procurement. This will aid the delivery of social, economic and environmental wellbeing objectives.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Category Management</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Halton has adopted a category management approach to procurement by aligning business requirements across the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">organisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. By working with wider partners we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">are starting to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> gain greater leverage, add</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> value and maximis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ing more</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> savings. As Halton is relatively small in terms of spend and leverage, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> can capture</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> internal aggregation to drive a category approach to procurement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">but would significantly gain if partners worked in a more aligned way.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We are working internally with Public Health </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">who joined local government April 2013. We are currently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> piloting a procurement support service to Halton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’s Clinical Commissioning Group which is developing strong integration with Halton BC, Public Health and wider partners.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> delivering a support service to Sefton MBC in order to lead and direct their organis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ation to achieve alignment with our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">procurement processes, practices</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and rules. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We continue to maintain a regional relationship with Merseyside Procurement Partnership (MPP) – Members include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">: Councils -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Halton; Sefton; Liverpool; St Helens; Knowsley; Wirral; C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">heshire </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">est </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&amp;C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">hester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">; Mersey Travel and Mersey Fire &amp; Rescue. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Purchase to Pay/ e Procurement</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Halton has developed internal automated process relationships between procurement and accounts payable into a seamless end-to-end process in order to improve efficiencies using e-procurement solutions. This is underpinned by:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Accurate categorisation of spend data in Agresso which provides reliable intelligence. This will facilitate cross-partner mapping and planning as we can data match common spend categories and suppliers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The implementation of an in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">-house early payment scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to suppliers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that integrates with Agresso.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Robust monitoring of transactions, suppliers, and purchase orders in order to stream line and reduce the activity through better compliance and automated processes.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt">Response to the specific topics:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">1. To what extent is local government procurement organised to deliver value for money and social, economic and environmental objectives, including stimulating the local economy? To what extent are local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">achieving the involvement of local residents in delivering value for money? To what extent are local authorities able to develop long-term relationships with contractors?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Firstly, Value for Money is secured from our commercial procurement concept as we aspire to publish all trading opportunities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">for spend from £1,000 upwards via T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he Chest in order that our practices are fully transparent. This enables market testing all spending decisions, this practice is designed to be proportionate to both risk and value and it allows opport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">unity to suppliers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">to tender or quote which supports the stimulation and growth of the local and SME economy.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Our spend </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">2012/13 demonstrated that 89% was with SMEs. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We are continually improving our approach to s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ocial value and not just when </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">consider</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the evaluation criterion which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> needs to be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> bespoke and proportionate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> but in order that it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> allows us to measure social value gains </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">as well as seek</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> best value in terms of both quality and price. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The social value gain needs to be embedded into the contract </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">through voluntary or mandatory </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">clauses in order to ensure this value is captured contractually and not just rhetoric </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in the bidder’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> submissions. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We are developing a social value policy and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> set of principles to be embedded into procurement where appropriate to ensure we firstly engage at the pre-procurement stage with potential bidders in order to educate and support as well as allowing bidders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to attend and contribute to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> an open forum to help us design service delivery to best deliver the outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> required</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We have strengthened</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the contract </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">management function</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to ensure it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> is more commercial in terms of ensuring that performance indicators are measured and challenged when not being achieved. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Halton is one of the four localities in England to take part in the Delivering Social Value in Health Programme. The programme aims to support the implementation of the Public Services (Social Value) Act 2012 locally. Halton will develop best practice of how social value can be gained particularly through health and wellbeing through procurement. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We commenced a campaign during 2010 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">for businesses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">which has continued to date in terms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of promoting our ‘New Ways of T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">rading’. This was underpinned by a series of business workshops which educated and supported the business community </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in local government procurement;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> registering and using </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he Chest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> as well as demonstrating our commitment in Halton to ensure transparency of opportunity and to make the process simple and clear. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Our process is risk based rather than value unlike the EU</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> financial</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> thresholds. This has enabled us to challenge and review our processes and practices</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to address what was termed as a bureaucratic and onerous historically in Halton by our business community.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We have clear performance indicators which are being embedded into our large</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> contracts which take account of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">how the main contractor can contribute to Employment, Learning and Skills growth in Halton. We also measure this through the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">transparency of opportunity for smaller contractors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> as part of their supply chain.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> This was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> applied and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> tested in contracts such as Building Schools for the Future (£60M) and Highways joint contract across Hal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ton and Warrington Councils (£70-100</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> over 10 years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">). This contractor has also relocated into the Borough.  Similar KPIs are being developed at present into Mersey Gateway Bridge contract (£600M). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">2. Do authorities take sufficient advantage of collaborative and joint procurement opportunities, including those available from central government? In addition, the Committee would welcome information on PFI contracts and their operation with local government.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Local Government does not take advantage enough of collaborative and joint procurement opportunities. Our perception of the barriers to this are; different rules in each organisation; the timings of contract end dates and the lack of motivation for one or more partner to extend their contract in order to align timings; lack of regional leadership and coordination; no mandate to drive collaboration jus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">t enthusiasm of the willing few</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and the perceived</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> threat of a ‘shared service’ if we procure together.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The solution could be; aligning rules and p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">rocesses; developing a partnership </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">approach to contract management i.e. one contract register which could be facilitated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">through an e-solution and sharing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> spend data in order that we have joint planning and i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">dentify aggregate opportunities. All of this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> requires strong commitment and clear </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cross-partner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> leadership to allow all of these opportunities to be explored and then implemented. We should approach procurement as ‘one buyer’.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> This doesn’t have to be a regional approach just a collaborative approach where more than one public sector partner works together.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Central government opportunities as well as other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">central purchasing bodies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> are mostly explored as part of our pre-procurement activi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ty in Halton to ensure we bench</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">mark in order to seek the best route to market.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In Halton we do have a PFI contract as part of BSF. We have an established LEP which is considered as part of the pre procurement process for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">construction spend and is bench</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">marked accordingly as this is a pre-procured route so can offer some value for money.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> This is a Joint Venture Company where Halton BC is a 10% shareholder.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">3. How can local authorities access the skills, expertise and capabilities to implement effective procurement strategies, including value for money and social and economic objectives? More specifically, does local government have sufficient understanding of its procurement expenditure and the markets for goods and services to deliver quality procurement strategies—locally and regionally. If not, how can deficiencies be addressed?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">authorities need to utilise Halton’s Commercial Procurement concept</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> which is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> designed, tested and implemented </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and is now being embraced by a few public sector partners. Halton has invested in the procurement to grow the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> skills</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> capabilities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> which has been underpinned by a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">clear strategy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and strong leadership and expertise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Other Local Authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">could </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">consider </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">sharing leadership in order to drive organisational change through procurement. This concept is currently being tested by Sefton MBC wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> have signed up to aligning their procurement rules, processes and practices to Halton’s and Halton is providing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">direct </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">leadership,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> training and support. Halton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> are also delivering a pilot to Halton Clinical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Commissioning Group with the intention of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">securing a contract from 2014 to deliver a procurement service. This is the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> start of driving wider partner </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">integration</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> through procurement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Halton aspires to develop such</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> relationships with other public sector partners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> as the demand is rapidly growing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There is a distinct lack of robust strategic procurement leadership within the public sector which may be as a result of not recruiting the right skill base or not valuing the skill that the right person will bring to lead whole organisational change? Funding pressures may be a barrier particularly in the public sector not recognising the opportunity of transforming services through procurement therefore not investing in this work stream and resourcing this concept.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">If we were to look overseas for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> New Zealand, there is a coordinated approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ‘Government Procurement Reform)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> led from central government to support local government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in procurement improvement. We need to establish a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">national approach, developing more formal cross partner support to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">challenge local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">procurement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> offer support, direction and solutions to be tailored at a local level.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Procurement sits in every organisation as we all buy, therefore standardised rules, processes,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and procedures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, should be encouraged as part of a national campaign. Our work reaches across public health and clinical commissioning groups as well as wider public sector partners. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Our commercial procurement concept focusses on Demand Management and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">upplier </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">elationship </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">anagement which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> underpin how we approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> our strategy to procurement as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Halton BC knows </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">its procurement expenditure and its markets and uses this to drive procurement priorities and opportunities. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">4. To what extent is risk in local government procurement and contracting understood and managed and contracting strategies adopted, which are tailored to product and supplier market places? More specifically, do local authorities maintain and operate effective client management functions and have they entered contractual arrangements which allow the flexibility to meet changing circumstances such as budget reductions or changes in the way a service has to be delivered?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Halton underpins all procurement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">activity with a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> risk assessment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">process (Risk Based Sourcing - RBS) for all spend below EU financial thresholds and this replaces the PQQ. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Understanding of risk is paramount and this sits at the start</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of the pre-procurement process as we focus on risk not value below EU.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">As part of this pre-procurement risk assessment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">process </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">officers explore risk in e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">very respect in order that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">risk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> identified </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and then</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">removed, reduced or managed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">throughout</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the procurement process and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the life of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">contract.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We do operate an effective client management function as we manage our procurement on a category basis and this links to contract management which sits with the client department but we maintain a commercial contract management function centrally and contract register.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We do build in at the pre-procurement stage as part of the risk assessment process a step to secure funding availability and approval in order to identify any risk; we work closely with our finance department. This allows us to build in to both the procurement process and contract management process lean procurement principles in order to respond to change.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Contract management needs to be more focussed on commercial challenge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e are developing a strategic approach to this by undertaking a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">root and branch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> approach to review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> contracts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">; this is one of our six building blocks – Supplier Relationship Management</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. This process will be seen as an audit of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> each</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> contract and its commercial outputs, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ensures compliance a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">nd will allow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the chance to challenge non-compliance and to understand how the contract can be used flexibly to adapt to changing requirements. The learning from this will allow us to greatly develop ever more flexible clauses so we can respond to pressures and external influences as they arise in a changing public sector canvass. This contract review will also highlight financial efficiencies and improvements that can be sought from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> review and challenge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">There are other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">vehicles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> which allow a more flexible approach to procurement such as Dynamic Purchasing Systems (DPS) which allow a procurement process to remain ‘open’ in order to encourage the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">best of breed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">’ into the supplier market at any stage and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">allow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> flexibility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> as to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">how we select these pre-procured providers to deliver services. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We are exploring such options.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">5. How is regularity and propriety of procurement secured and are the arrangements for detecting and addressing impropriety and fraud effective?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Regularity and propriety of procurement is secured in Halton as we utilise an e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">-tendering portal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> called The Chest which maintains a full audit trail of procurement activity. We have robust procurement rules and control procurement centrally to drive compliance. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Our Executive Board play a full part in procurement in terms of our rules requiring decisions to be made at Board level such as spend approval over £1M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> before commencement of procurement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and waiver requests where our rules cannot be followed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Our Business Efficiency Board undertake a scrutiny role, they select a number of procurement exercises to ‘test’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> annually</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in order to evaluate the end to end process and to make recommendations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">xecutive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Board</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in terms of the rules. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Our intern</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">al audit team have scrutinised T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he Chest system and processes as well as select annually a number of procurement exercise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to audit, more so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> those of material value.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The Audit Commission also reviewed our new ways of working and the use of The Chest and commended this as “Much strengthened procurement and significantly improved procurement arrangements as a key mechanism for delivering the efficiency programme across the Council” (Annual governance report 2010/11). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Our central role is guidance, support and advice as well as challenge and moderation. In Halton we do adopt a ‘team around the table’ approach in order to bring the service specialist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> together with the procurement specialists. All of our processes are standard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and we have fully implemented our risk based approach, standard documentation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and a web based process which are used before we use T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he Chest to facilitate the actual procurement exercise.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">6. Is local authority procurement fully transparent, audited effectively and does it provide appropriate mechanisms for redress? Specifically, are the arrangements for securing the accountability of procured services and goods to local authorities and local residents adequate and effective? More specifically, to what extent are local authorities able to provide assurance to central government that value for money (in the broadest sense of the term) is delivered?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Our l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ocal authority procurement is fully transparent but this isn’t the case in many public sector organisations. This is demonstrated as all procurement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">above £1,000 is processed via T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he Chest.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Mechanisms for redress: The Remedies D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">irective is there for EU value procurement. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">For spend b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">elow EU</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">we take complaints and challenges very seriously. W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e have a complaints procedure b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ut we do adopt the principles of transparency in terms of feedback by providing a rank position for all bidders </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">for procurement activity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">below EU. If additional feedback is requested we wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ll respond</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. EU </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">principles are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">adopted for all pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">curement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> activity.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The whole concept we have designed, tested and embedded demonstrates how we can assure central government that we deliver value for money. This is underpinned by a clear and measurable strategy and our simple Procurement Standing Orders.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt">Conclusion:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We recognise in Halton that we have made significant progress in securing a commercial procurement concept which is fully embedded into the organisation. We commend this concept and approach to all public sector organisations as it clearly demonstrates value for money, reduces risk significantly, removes bureaucracy and benefits the supply market as well as the public sector. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We recognise that public sector organisations have different priorities and demands and there are significant variations in performance which means there is greater scope for improvement. Some procurement practices are too ‘traditional’, under resourced and lack procurement vision and leadership. But we all face the same pressures economically, socially and environmentally and we all spend public money therefore, we all must be accountable and we all must secure value for money which is clearly demonstrable from the suc</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cess in Halton. </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>